8027. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 25306538
T1  - Cystic ovary and antiandrogen therapy in acne patients: Study of 95 cases
A1  - Zafar Sadeque J.B.M.
A1  - Garfar Chy A.
A1  - Shahidullah M.
A1  - Kamal M. 
Y1  - 1995//
N2  - Excess androgenic hormones play some role in producing acne vulgaris. Ovarian cyst is one source of excess androgenic hormones in females. Antibiotic therapy may not be effective in treating acne patients having concomitant cystic ovaries. Anti-androgens therapy may prove worthy in these cases. Female acne patients were screened to assess the incidence of cystic ovaries. We also wanted to evaluate the antibiotic and hormone therapies in treating such acne patients. We randomly selected 95 female acne patients in which acne was diagnosed clinically, and ovarian cysts were detected by ultrasonography. In selective 11 cases we estimated blood levels of related androgenic hormones. Antibiotic therapy was administered in 87 cases. Hormone therapy was given in 30 cases of cystic overy group including 19 failed cases. All cases were followed up for 1 year. Cysts were found in 67.4% (64/95) cases mostly in middle aged patients having acne for more than 12 months. Hirsutism and menstrual disturbances were found to have raised free testosterone, FSH and LH in their sera. Antibiotic therapy showed 59.6% (34/57) good response and 75.3% (43/57) relapse in cystic ovary group while 80% (24/30) good response and 33.3% (10/30) relapse in normal ovary group. Hormone therapy (anti-androgen) in cystic ovaries group showed 93.3% (28/30) good response and 10% (3/30) relapse. Persistant acne associated with cystic ovaries with or without hirsutism, menstrual disorder or obesity is a common occurrence, so hormone therapy with anti-androgen may be considered for these patients.
