8082. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 24088308
T1  - A comparison between monoclonal and polyclonal assay of luteinizing hormone in polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Jahanfar S.
A1  - Garrett D.K.
A1  - Eden J.A. 
Y1  - 1994//
N2  - The main objective of this study was to compare two different methods for measuring the serum luteinizing hormone (LH) in patients with polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS). Transabdominal ultrasounds were performed in a serles of 96 women, aged 15 to 45 who volunteered for the study of PCOS. Biochemical tests including testosterone (T), dehydroepiandrostenedione sulphate (DHEAS) and sex hormone binding globulin (SHBG) were measured in serum and free androgen index (FAI) was calculated. Using two methods for diagnosis of PCOS (ultrasound and biochemical) those with discordant results were excluded from the study. Fifty-three subjects remained from whom 24 were considered as having the PCOS and 29 were classified as non-PCOS. Serum concentrations of LH were measured by two methods including Amerlex-M radioimmunoassay (LH(a), a polyclonal assay) and Stratus Fluorometric Enzyme Immunoassay (FEI, (LH(s), a monoclonal assay). Overall measurements of serum LH by LH(s) assay gave values that were 13% lower than LH measured by LH(a) (p < 0.0001). However, the LH(s) assay had higher specificity than LH(a) method. Also, comparison between two groups of subjects with or without PCOS showed that LH(s) was significantly higher in subjects with PCO (p < 0.05) while there were no significant difference for LH(a). LH(s)/LH(a) ratio was calculated as a measure of assay comparability and was significantly correlated with LH(s) in both groups of PCOS and normal subjects (p < 0.01). This study suggests that the monoclonal Stratus assay which utilises two antibodies may more accurately reflect bioactive LH in patients with PCOS.
