8084. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 24267400
T1  - How reliable are biochemical tests in the diagnosis of polycystic ovary syndrome?
A1  - Jahanfar S.
A1  - Eden J.A.
A1  - Garrett D.K. 
Y1  - 1994//
N2  - The present study was undertaken to investigate the accuracy of biochemical indices to detect polycystic ovary (PCO) compared with ultrasound. Reference ranges for luteinizing hormone (LH), testosterone (T), sex hormone binding globulin (SHBG), dehydroepiandrosterone sulphate (DHEAS) and free androgen index (FAI) were first determined using a group of scan-normal subjects with no clinical or biochemical evidence of polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) (controls, n = 21). Ninety-three subjects were divided into two groups using ultrasound examination only; subjects with no evidence of PCO (scan-normals, n = 44) and a group of subjects with scan evidence of PCO (scan-PCOs, n = 49). The results were as follows: (1) using ultrasound to define PCO, biochemical testing was 55% sensitive and 63% specific with an efficiency of 59%, (2) testosterone (T) was the best single biochemical test to detect PCO with the sensitivity of 38%, (3) when a combination of test was evaluated, T, DHEAS or FAI was found to be the best indicator of PCO, (4) the accuracy of the LH/FSH ratio was very low suggesting that the measurement of this ratio should be abandoned, and (5) ovarian volume was correlated with SHBG, FAI and LH, suggesting that this ovarian measurement could be a useful measure of sex hormone production.
