8094. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 24354878
T1  - Control of luteinizing hormone secretion in polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Balen A.H.
A1  - Rose M. 
Y1  - 1994//
N2  - Women with the polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) who hypersecrete luteinizing hormone (LH) have an increased risk of infertility and miscarriage. It appears that disordered ovarian-pituitary feedback leads to hypersecretion of LH, possibly because of a perturbed secretion of non-steroidal ovarian hormones. The authors present the hypothesis that there is a new ovarian hormone, which has been named gonadotrophin surge attenuating or inhibiting factor (GnSAF/GnSIF). It is proposed that a deficiency of GnSAF/GnSIF might lead to hypersecretion of LH. In a population of 1741 women with PCOS, an elevated serum LH concentration (> 10 IU/l) was associated with an increased rate of menstrual cycle disturbance and infertility. Subfertile women with PCOS were studied during ovulation induction with laparoscopic ovarian diathermy and during in vitro fertilization. Laparoscopic ovarian diathermy induces ovulation in women with PCOS and has the advantage of lowering serum concentrations of LH. It was found that unilateral ovarian diathermy resulted in ovulation from both ovaries, indicating a role for ovarian-pituitary feedback in the mechanism of both ovulation and hypersecretion of LH. In a retrospective study of 538 patients undergoing IVF, PCOS was detected by ultrasound scan in 45.3 per cent of patients who miscarried compared with 31.4 per cent of those with ongoing pregnancies (P = 0.0038). In the 182 women with PCOS, there was a highly significant reduction in the rate of miscarriage when buserelin was used to achieve pituitary desensitization followed by ovarian stimulation with human menopausal gonadotrophins (hMG) compared with the use of clomiphene and hMG (15/74 versus 51/108, P = 0.0003). However, there was no improvement in miscarriage rates with pituitary desensitization in patients who did not have PCOS. These results suggest that it is high follicular phase levels of LH that profoundly affect oocyte and embryo quality and that suppression of LH levels with buserelin returns the miscarriage rate to the rate seen in women with normal ovaries. In order to study the existence of GnSAF/GnSIF, preparations of female rat pituicytes were cultured and used as a bioassay for the effects of purified human follicular fluid on gonadotrophin secretion. The bioassay was characterized in detail and the effects of inhibin quantified. A preparation of recently purified GnSAF inhibited both gonadotrophin releasing hormone (GnRH)-stimulated follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and LH secretion and was not inhibited by treatment with an anti-inhibin antiserum. Thus GnSAF appears to be a novel peptide hormone which is distinct from inhibin. There is evidence that hypersecretion of LH is due to perturbed non-steroidal ovarian-pituitary feedback and it is proposed that a deficiency of GnSAF may lead to this common cause of infertility and miscarriage.
