8120. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 23091314
T1  - Polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Falcone T.
A1  - Granger L.
A1  - Bourque J.
A1  - Hemmings R.
A1  - Miron P. 
Y1  - 1993//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a clinical syndrome that is commonly found in anovulatory women, as well as in some women with no apparent endocrine disturbance. This syndrome is associated with infertility, endometrial cancer, and metabolic changes such as hyperinsulinemia and an atherogenic lipoprotein profile. The diagnosis of this syndrome has traditionally relied on serum measurements of gonadotropin and androgen. Ultrasonography has recently been introduced as a method for confirmation of the diagnosis. Management of the infertile patient with PCOS continues to be a challenge. Ovulation induction with the usual agents has a lower achievement and pregnancy rate compared with results with other anovulatory disorders. Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome constitutes a major risk in PCOS patients, and the risk has not decreased substantially in spite of the introduction of new ovulation induction strategies. Surgical treatment of PCOS has been reintroduced through the laparoscope. The precise role of surgery in the management of PCOS patients still remains to be determined. Treatment of hirsutism in PCOS patients has not changed fundamentally over the last decade, with the major emphasis on the use of an oral contraceptive agent. Research into the etiology and pathogenesis of PCOS has revealed a more complex picture than originally postulated. In addition to the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian abnormalities that have been described, other important endocrinologic disturbances have been reported. The potential roles of growth hormone, the insulin-like growth factors and their binding proteins, and insulin in the pathophysiology of this syndrome have recently been described. Because of the prevalence of PCOS and associated endometrial cancer among women and its relationship to abnormal carbohydrate metabolism and obesity, its identification and management may be of significant public health importance.
