T1  - Polycystic ovaries as a relative protective factor for bone mineral loss in young women with amenorrhea
A1  - Di Carlo C.
A1  - Shoham Z.
A1  - MacDougall J.
A1  - Patel A.
A1  - Hall M.L.
A1  - Jacobs H.S. 
Y1  - 1992//
N2  - Objective: To examine the impact of polycystic ovaries (PCO) on bone mineral density in amenorrheic women of reproductive age. Design(s): A retrospective analysis and comparison of polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) with non-PCOS amenorrheic women. A subgroup of patients with ultrasound (US)- diagnosed PCO was also investigated. Setting(s): Specialist clinic in reproductive endocrinology. Patients, Participants: Six hundred ten consecutive cases, mean age of 29.8 +/- 7.5 years, with current history of amenorrhea of various causes. Main Outcome Measure(s): Bone mineral density in the lumbar spine (L1 to L4) as measured by dual energy x ray absorptiometry, in relation to PCOS, US-diagnosed PCO, and US findings of normal ovaries. Result(s): Amenorrheic patients with PCOS were found to be younger (P < 0.001), with higher body mass index (P < 0.001), were more estrogenized, as measured by endometrial thickness and uterine cross-sectional area (P < 0.001), and had higher bone mineral density (P < 0.001) compared with non-PCOS amenorrheic patients. Conclusion(s): Patients with amenorrhea because of PCOS and those with US-diagnosed PCO have a higher bone density compared with amenorrheic patients with normal ovaries as detected by US scan.
