8243. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 20223442
T1  - Gynaecology: Insulin resistance and the polycystic ovary syndrome
A1  - Conway G.S. 
Y1  - 1990//
N2  - The biochemical abnormalities associated with the polycystic ovary syndrome have intriguing abilities to fuel dispute as to the origin of the disease. Recent reviews have observed that the classical picture of raised serum LH and androgen concentrations and enlarged ovaries may be a result of a primary defect in the hypothalamus, the adrenal gland or the ovary. Now there is a fourth protagonist to be considered: the association between hyperinsulinaemia and the polycystic ovary syndrome. This account reviews our understanding of the clinical and biochemical spectrum of the polycystic ovary syndrome and traces the historical path of insulin resistance into the picture. Finally, the role of insulin in the polycystic ovary syndrome is considered in the light of new data which put this association in perspective. The importance of gaining a better understanding of the nature of this syndrome is underlined by several facts. Firstly, polycystic ovaries are common. Over recent years at the Middlesex Hospital we have seen nearly 1000 women with the polycystic ovary syndrome, accounting for about half of the patients investigated in reproductive endocrine clinics. There is a remarkable uniformity in the high prevalence of polycystic ovaries in patients complaining of oligomenorrhoea, hirsutism or acne among the growing number of centres that use ultrasound as the basis for diagnosis. Secondly, the recognition that previously unhelpful diagnoses such as idiopathic hirsutism in fact largely constitute a mild form of the polycystic ovary syndrome will help us on the road to better directed treatments. Lastly, on the subject of therapy, directed treatments. Lastly, on the subject of therapy, none of the drugs used at present to control the various symptoms of the polycystic ovary syndrome is without major worrying side-effects. There is now great pressure from both prescribers and recipients of these drugs for alternatives. Exploration of the role of insulin in the expression of this syndrome may lead to new management.
